> A combination of Spanish delights. A very simple Spanish butter bean stew using fresh tomatoes, rich in flavour and colour. A great little dish on its own! It's difficult to go into a tapas bar and not find this on the menu. And of course, a traditional combination of paprika and pork that will send wonderful, zingy notes to your taste buds.

Preheat your #oven{} to 200 degrees.

Cut the @onion{1/2}(peeled and finely sliced) in half, peel and slice into half moon shapes. Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove} (or use a #garlic press{} if you have one). Chop the @vine tomatoes{2} into eighths and heat a #medium-sized saucepan{} with a splash of @olive oil{}. Once warm, add your onions and garlic. Fry for ~{5%mins} until they become soft, transparent and begin to colour.

Add your tomato to the #saucepan{} and cook for a further ~{2%mins}. Drain the @butter beans{1} and add them to your tomato, followed by the @chicken stock pot{1/2}, @tomato puree{1.5}, @bay leaf{1} and the @water{75}. Place a lid on the saucepan and leave to simmer for ~{30%mins}, stirring occasionally to ensure it isn't catching on the bottom or becoming too dry.

> If it does start to become dry, just add a splash of water.

Cut any larger @new potatoes{1} in half (no need to peel). Boil a #pot{} of water with a pinch of @salt{} and add your potatoes. Cook for ~{15%mins}. Meanwhile, remove the core and slice the @red pepper{1} into thick strips about 2cm wide. Place these on a lined #baking tray{}.

Season the @pork medallion{2} with a good pinch of @salt{} and rub the @smoked paprika{1.5} all over the meat. Place this on top of your bed of peppers and generously drizzle with @olive oil{}, before putting on the top shelf of your oven for ~{15-17%mins} or until cooked through.

> The pork is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Your potatoes should be thoroughly cooked now.

> The potatoes are cooked when you can easily slip a knife through.

Drain and lightly crush with a #fork{} (don't mash them). Heat a #medium-sized frying pan{} with a splash of @olive oil{}. Add your potatoes to the pan. Fry for ~{4%mins}, until they start to crisp.

Your butter bean stew should be a lovely thick consistency now, without too much liquid remaining. Season with a pinch of @salt{} and a few good grinds of @black pepper{} to taste. Once your pork is out of your oven cut it into thin slices.

Finally, time to plate up! Serve your pork slices on top of your crushed new potatoes and red peppers, top with your butter bean stew. Dig in!